<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
At 8.30 BBC2 and ITV each launch a new run of a well established factual
series. In Far Flung Floyd (BBC2) the most entertaining of today's
television cooks, Keith Floyd, presents the first of seven programmes
reporting on the food of the Far East. He begins in Vietnam, cooking a stew
for an army volley ball team. In another series of The Cook Report (ITV) the
increasingly large Roger Cook sets out again to stick his foot -
figuratively and, when necessary, literally - in the doors of the world's
villains.
Switched At Birth is one of those productions for which the ITV chiefs would
like to move 'News At 10'. An American mini series, it tells of the parents
of a baby girl who discover that they cannot be her biological parents. It
begins at 9.00, continues at 10.40 and ends tomorrow.
In Scarfe On Class the cartoonist makes one of his periodic forays into Big
Subjects: his previous programmes on art, sex and the afterlife will be
repeated on forthcoming Tuesdays. In today's new programme he learns how to
acquire the right accent, and even a lordship (9.50 BBC2).
</TEXT>
