<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lib Dems touch nerve over rail
privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OFF-PEAK rail services to Christchurch are to be cut by half from this
autumn, the Liberal Democrats claimed yesterday as rail privatisation and
law and order dominated opening exchanges in the first week of by-election
campaigning.
Mr Nick Harvey, MP for Devon North and the party's transport spokesman, said
off-peak services from London to the Dorset seaside town would be 'slashed'
from two trains per hour to one from October as part of a 'slim-down' to
pave the way for privatisation.
As the party sought to exploit discontent at the government's sell-off
plans, Mrs Diana Maddock, the Liberal Democrat candidate, released the
results of a survey showing an overwhelming majority of local people wanted
through ticketing and discount cards to continue after privatisation.
'It is all too apparent that rail privatisation has become one of the most
unpopular policies of an already unpopular government,' Mrs Maddock said.
As Network SouthEast said its winter timetable plans had yet to be
finalised, Mr Robert Hayward, the Tory candidate, described the predictions
of impending service cuts as 'speculation'.
Mr Hayward - the former MP for Kingswood and a strong supporter of rail
privatisation - has made no bones about his views on the subject being very
different from those of rail enthusiast Mr Robert Adley, the maverick Tory
MP whose death prompted the by-election.
The Conservatives, who are defending a majority of 23,000 in what promises
to be a crucial test of Mr John Major's battered authority, used a visit by
Mr David Maclean, a home office minister, to attack the Liberal Democrats'
record on law and order, described by Mr Maclean as the 'key issue' of the
July 29 by-election.
But with no member of the cabinet having yet set foot in Christchurch, there
is an impression the Tory campaign has got off to a slow start.
Law and order was also touched on by Labour during a visit by Mrs Margaret
Beckett, the deputy leader. Mr Nigel Lickley, the Labour candidate, said
Labour had recently tabled proposals in the Commons that would aid crime
prevention, reduce crime and curb offending while on bail.
