<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour deputy leader 'nervous'
about pension privatisation scheme
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS MARGARET Beckett, Labour's deputy leader, said yesterday she would be
'very nervous' about any move to enable people to opt out of the basic state
pension scheme.
Campaigning in Christchurch, she said private pensions were 'admirable as
long as they are something that give people the freedom to top up' the basic
state scheme.
While Labour favoured improving the current system to take account of
contemporary family and work patterns, it was not looking for savings at the
expense of 'people already struggling with their pensions'.
Her remarks came after Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, welcomed
proposals by Labour MP Mr Frank Field - chairman of the Commons' social
security committee - for privatising state pensions. Mr Lilley said the
basic pension would remain as a 'building block'.
</TEXT>
