<HEADLINE>
FT  10 JUL 93 / Murdoch abandons NY Post to its fate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Rupert Murdoch yesterday abandoned his efforts to buy the financially
crippled New York Post  - a move which seemed likely to spell the end of the
192-year-old tabloid, America's oldest continuously published newspaper.
News Corporation, the media empire headed by Mr Murdoch, said it had been
unable to agree cost savings needed to guarantee the paper's survival in
negotiations with the paper's 11 unions.
The Post has been operating for four months under the protection of the
bankruptcy court and News Corporation has been managing the business since
March 29, pending negotiations with the court on a purchase price.
However, on Tuesday News Corporation served notice on the court that it
would walk away from the management contract at 4pm yesterday unless the
unions agreed to the cost-cutting concessions it had been demanding.
Mr Patrick Purcell, president of its News America Publishing subsidiary,
announced shortly after 4pm that the concessions had not been forthcoming
and 'News Corp has no choice but to cancel our management agreement. It is a
sad day for all of us.'
Staff were told no paper would be published today and they should clear
their desks before the Post building was padlocked.
Asked whether News Corporation might reconsider its position if the unions
suddenly caved in, a spokesman for Mr Murdoch said: 'News Corporation,
they're gone.'
The fate of the Post will now be decided in the bankruptcy courts. Unless an
alternative buyer emerges, which seems unlikely, the court will have little
choice but to liquidate the business.
Mr Murdoch was hailed as a last-chance saviour when he took over management
of the Post in March after months of uncertainty over the paper's finances
and ownership.
The paper is still losing money heavily - over Dollars 300,000 (Pounds
200,000) a week, according to News Corporation  - and the demise of New
York's smallest but raciest tabloid would give breathing space to its rivals
in this overcrowded market, the Daily News and Newsday.
</TEXT>
